I think the engine is fine. 1) it's supposed to withstand immense temperatures, 2) the fire was not located on the engine, it was at the access port and ground connection.
Presumably hopper hopped an inch or so, even with tethers and that separated the connector to the fuel line just enough to make it leak and then when it came back down maybe it bent the connector or something.
Unusual what happened with the access port though, usually absolutely nothing should come out of it.
Come sunrise and lift of road closure we may get closeups and better views of the connector.
At most some cables below may be burned that need to be replaced. Development engine has a lot of extra sensors and thin wires.
I think we should not hope for a hover today. Inspection and potential replacement of fuel connections and other parts may take longer

I love all the Area 51 hype that still comes up. What's ironic is that the military moved all the current & most sensitive stuff to an updated facility in southern Utah several years ago, but people are still obsessed with the old place in NM. For a while during the transition I could see both bases from satellite (which was profoundly uninteresting), and then some areas got blanked over again once they were set up.

And folks, don't go looking for the new base. It's in the middle of freaking nowhere with no road access for normal vehicles, no nearby travel supplies etc. You'll end up dying in the mountains and your corpse will get scavenged by coyotes; and if you accidentally get close enough to the actual zone, even your emergency GPS transponder won't save you because there's no civilian relay to the net.
